update: so I found a way around this if anyone else asks but I still think it should be implemented differently so you don't have to do all this:

You can't use .bind in an expression but you can however use lodash curry:

```
$scope.sort = {
    	column: _.curry(function(cohort,group) {
    		return // your sorting thing
    	}),
    };
```

and then on the attribute:

```
<th ng-repeat="cohort in cohorts" st-sort="sort.column(cohort)" st-skip-natural="true">{{cohort}}</th>
```

this still passes the row as the first argument and allows you to pass your own argument second and most importantly doesn't break your sort function in smart-table.js:

```
        function sort () {
          index++;
          predicate = ng.isFunction(getter(scope)) ? getter(scope) : attr.stSort;
       ...
       }
```

ng.isFunction(getter(scope)) would typically call the function if you declare the attribute as st-sort="someFunction(foo)" but for some reason with the _.curry because it creates a wrapper function it doesn't call the function and thus doesn't break anything.

