@dstansby Yes, you'll note I left some comments there. I'd really like to go standards-based if possible, but I'm not seeing anything obvious, so I guess we'll have to blaze our own trail here. It's not clear to me how your solution handles negative numbers, but that may be one of the big issues here - considering you generally want the negative sign on the largest of the numbers, usually, but if you're allowing flexible tokens, it can get complicated.

Additionally, there's the question of rounding vs. expansion. If I have something that's like `timedelta(days=4, hours=3)` and I format it with `'{:H02}h'`, does that give me `'99'` (including the days) or `'3h'` (days only). How about if it's `'{:H}'.format(timedelta(hours=3, minutes=6)`, should it be `'3'` Or `'3.1'`?

I think the two general approaches here would be "best effort" and "explicit specification". With "best effort", we'd make a best guess at what you were going for and the guarantee would be that however we formatted it, the number represents *all* the components of the `timedelta`. With "explicit specification", we'd basically want a more intricate formatting mini-spec that has some components representing sub-components and some representing "all the components of the timedelta". It may be that these concerns are orthogonal and so both could be represented in different parts of the tokens.

