@esc you could use a modifier to trigger updates in such a case where you want to use latest as version tag for your docker image. Something like `cf sync my-stack.yml --parameter my-stack.updateDate=2016-03-24`. If you use the `updateDate` parameter as a tag for your instances and as a dummy variable inside the user-data of your instance, it will trigger a redeploy whenever it changes. 
This way you would have a traceability for the software version used on your instances and trigger updates as you like it without the need to recreate the stack.

Or, don't use latest ;-)

If the exception is coming directly from C++ (i.e. not through a Python function), you should just catch it directly rather than catching `error_already_set`.

If the exception is propagated through Python, you'll need to define a custom python exception type and look for it when catching an `error_already_set`.  In your current example, you can do this by changing the exception translator to:
```C++
    static py::exception<pyMOOSException> ex(m, "pyMOOSException", PyExc_RuntimeError);
    py::register_exception_translator([](std::exception_ptr p) {
        try {
            if (p) std::rethrow_exception(p);
        } catch (const pyMOOSException &e) {
            // Set pyMOOSException as the active python error
            ex(e.what());
        }
    }
```
then when you catch `error_already_set` you can check whether the Python-side pyMOOSException is the active exception with:
```C++
try { ... }
catch (const py::error_already_set &e) {
    auto py_moos_exc = py::module::import("modulename").attr("pyMOOSException");
    if (e.matches(py_moos_exc.ptr())) {
        // intercepted a pyMOOSException
    } else {
        throw; // Some other python exception: rethrow it to the default exception translator
    }
}
```

You can simplify that a bit if you make the `ex` variable a global instead a function-static variable; then you don't have to get `py_moos_exc` via module lookup: you can just use `e.matches(ex.ptr())` directly instead.

